</description><dc:creator xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/">ankur</dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 26 Nov 2016 14:53:57 +0000</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="false">tag:ankursinha.in,2016-11-26:/2016/11/26/two-new-planets-for-neuroscientists.html</guid><category>Fedora</category><category>Community</category><category>Computational neuroscience</category><category>Git</category></item><item><title>Quickly scripting a grid-search for parameter tuning</title><link>http://ankursinha.in/2016/08/27/quickly-scripting-a-grid-search-for-parameter-tuning.html</link><description>&lt;p class="first last"&gt;Finding the right set of parameters is quite important in a lot of research - machine learning and computational neuroscience are two fields that I know of. I recently had to ascertain the optimal parameter set for my simulations too. I came up with a quick script to do it for me.&lt;/p&gt;
</description><dc:creator xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/">ankur</dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Aug 2016 10:10:04 +0100</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="false">tag:ankursinha.in,2016-08-27:/2016/08/27/quickly-scripting-a-grid-search-for-parameter-tuning.html</guid><category>Computational neuroscience</category><category>Fedora</category><category>Git</category><category>Programming</category><category>Python</category></item><item><title>Checking your LaTeX sources for spelling errors with Hunspell</title><link>http://ankursinha.in/2016/06/02/checking-your-latex-sources-for-spelling-errors-with-hunspell.html</link><description>&lt;p class="first last"&gt;For command line users that write in &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://latex-project.org/intro.html"&gt;LaTeX&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a class="reference external" href="http://hunspell.github.io/"&gt;Hunspell&lt;/a&gt; is a great tool to check spellings.&lt;/p&gt;
</description><dc:creator xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/">ankur</dc:creator><pubDate>Thu, 02 Jun 2016 11:42:00 +0100</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="false">tag:ankursinha.in,2016-06-02:/2016/06/02/checking-your-latex-sources-for-spelling-errors-with-hunspell.html</guid><category>Fedora</category><category>Git</category><category>LaTeX</category><category>Linux</category><category>Vim</category></item><item><title>Some tips and tricks for running simulations on a cluster</title><link>http://ankursinha.in/2016/05/31/some-tips-and-tricks-for-running-simulations-on-a-cluster.html</link><description>&lt;p class="first last"&gt;I use the cluster here at university to run my simulations in &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://github.com/nest/nest-simulator"&gt;Nest&lt;/a&gt;. This post documents some tips and tricks I've come up with to make my cluster tasks easier.&lt;/p&gt;
</description><dc:creator xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/">ankur</dc:creator><pubDate>Tue, 31 May 2016 19:17:32 +0100</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="false">tag:ankursinha.in,2016-05-31:/2016/05/31/some-tips-and-tricks-for-running-simulations-on-a-cluster.html</guid><category>Bash</category><category>Computational neuroscience</category><category>Git</category><category>Linux</category><category>NEST</category><category>Programming</category><category>Fedora</category></item><item><title>Calliope - helping you keep a diary - in LaTeX!</title><link>http://ankursinha.in/2016/03/05/calliope-helping-you-keep-a-diary-in-latex.html</link><description>&lt;p class="first last"&gt;Most researchers keep a research journal where we note down our musings, notes and so on. While a paper diary is still quite common, I'd really prefer something on my laptop/computer. There are various applications out there for journal writing, but none of them really match up to good old &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://en.wikibooks.org/wiki/LaTeX"&gt;LaTeX&lt;/a&gt;. I've written a simple script that makes it really easy to maintain a journal using LaTeX - &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://github.com/sanjayankur31/calliope"&gt;Calliope&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
</description><dc:creator xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/">ankur</dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 05 Mar 2016 14:07:52 +0000</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="false">tag:ankursinha.in,2016-03-05:/2016/03/05/calliope-helping-you-keep-a-diary-in-latex.html</guid><category>Fedora</category><category>Git</category><category>LaTeX</category><category>Linux</category><category>Calliope</category></item><item><title>New Zaphod release - v0.5.7</title><link>http://ankursinha.in/2016/02/28/new-zaphod-release-v0-5-7.html</link><description>&lt;p class="first last"&gt;I've released a new version of &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://github.com/sanjayankur31/zaphod"&gt;Zaphod&lt;/a&gt; - A LaTeX change tracking tool that I've been working on recently.&lt;/p&gt;
</description><dc:creator xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/">ankur</dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Feb 2016 16:52:27 +0000</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="false">tag:ankursinha.in,2016-02-28:/2016/02/28/new-zaphod-release-v0-5-7.html</guid><category>LaTeX</category><category>Programming</category><category>Git</category><category>Fedora</category><category>Zaphod</category></item><item><title>Zaphod - a LaTeX change tracking tool</title><link>http://ankursinha.in/2016/02/13/zaphod-a-latex-change-tracking-tool.html</link><description>&lt;p class="first last"&gt;Introducing &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://github.com/sanjayankur31/zaphod"&gt;Zaphod&lt;/a&gt; - a &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://www.python.org/"&gt;Python&lt;/a&gt; script that attempts to help &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/LaTeX"&gt;LaTeX&lt;/a&gt; users collaborate over their academic writing. It uses the power of &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Git_(software)"&gt;Git&lt;/a&gt; to track changes, &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://www.ctan.org/pkg/latexdiff?lang=en"&gt;latexdiff&lt;/a&gt; to generate a PDF with annotated additions and removals from the document, and provides a simple interactive review tool that lets the user pick what changes they want to accept. You can use Zaphod to track changes in your LaTeX documents.&lt;/p&gt;
</description><dc:creator xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/">ankur</dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 13 Feb 2016 17:16:24 +0000</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="false">tag:ankursinha.in,2016-02-13:/2016/02/13/zaphod-a-latex-change-tracking-tool.html</guid><category>LaTeX</category><category>Programming</category><category>Git</category><category>Fedora</category><category>Zaphod</category></item></channel></rss>